                    <h2>How to Use with the Team</h2>
                    <p><b>Analytics</b> is the best place to start to get an overall picture of performance, before you dive into the details.  </p>
        <p>To do this, you must understand your:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Forecast Value</li>
            <li>Forecast Risk: Top 5 High Risk Opportunities</li>
            <li>Top 5 Must Win Opportunities</li>
            <li>Top 5 Develop Opportunities</li>
        </ul>
		<p>These areas of analysis are explored in this section.</p>
                    <div class="more_info">
					
        <h3>Forecast Value</h3>
        <p>Forecast Value shows your:</p>
        <ul>
            <li> Goal</li>
            <li>Won revenue and any gap to goal</li>
            <li>Projected revenue (some companies refer to this as Commit)</li>
            <li>Possible revenue (some companies refer to the is Upside) in the period</li>
            <li>Unlikely revenue – opportunities that are too early in a sales cycle or insufficiently advanced </li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>If you are using Dealmaker Smart Sales Playbook, your <b>Projected</b> revenue is any opportunity with a close probability of 70% or greater, and adequate time left in the period to close.</p>
        <p>And your <b>Possible</b> revenue is any opportunity that has reached 40% close probability and still has enough time in the period to close.  </p>
        <p>If you are not using Dealmaker Smart Sales Playbook, the parameters that define <b>Projected</b> or <b>Possible</b> are configured during the Dealmaker Sales Performance Manager setup process.</p>
        
        <p>If you manage revenue Billing separately to Booking, there may be a difference between the Bookings or Invoiced amount and what you forecast using your company's Revenue Recognition principles.</p>
        <p>You can  extend or 'nudge' your forecast period by one month to see what deals from the next period that it might be possible to accelerate . (This is done by selecting the <b>Extend Forecast Date by One Month</b> checkbox in the <b>Report</b> drop-down.)</p>
        
        <p>Forecast Value gives you the current state of your sales forecast for a specific period and for a specific Revenue Type.  </p>
        <p>To maximize the likelihood of achieving or exceeding the forecast, you need to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li> look at any deals that present a risk to the forecast</li>
            <li>focus on your must-win deals for the period</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Forecast Risk: Top 5 High Risk Opportunities</h3>
        <p>Forecast Risk: Top 5 High Risk Opportunities shows the deals that present a potentially high risk to your forecast. High Risk Deals require your immediate attention to get them on the right track.</p>
        <p>In many cases, the problem with your Forecast is that the opportunities that are included here are often marked as Forecasted or Commit by the sales person using only their subjective assessment.  There are certainly situations where this is an accurate assessment, but statistically only 50% of deals that are forecasted actually close.</p>
        <p>The best way to accurately assess whether a deal belongs in the Forecast is to have an objective and scientific assessment of risk. Look for risks in the forecasted deals in order to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>determine how to mitigate those risks</li>
            <li>reduce those unpleasant surprises of deal slippage or late-stage deal losses</li>
        </ul>
       
        <p>The High Risk criteria have been set by your system administrator, and should include:</p>
        <ul>
            <li> abnormally large deals</li>
            <li>opportunities that are moving more slowly than your typical winning sales cycle</li>
            <li>opportunities that have not been updated over a material time period</li>
        </ul>
        
        <p>In addition, you may have other risk factors identified that indicate High Risk.  We recommend that when you are assessing High Risk, you also consider:</p>
        <ul>
            <li> Compelling Event</li>
            <li>proven Unique Business Value</li>
            <li>Competitive Strategy</li>
            <li>evidence of a positive relationship with the Decision Maker</li>
            <li>Inside Support</li>
            <li>whether you have a complete understanding of the customer’s business problem</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If you use Dealmaker Smart Opportunity Manager, we strongly recommend performing a Test &amp; Improve on all High Risk opportunities. </p>
        <p>(If you have another mechanism to assess or strategize an opportunity, you should apply that process to all High Risk deals.) </p>
        <p>At the end of the Test &amp; Improve, you should define your strategy to mitigate the risk, modify the projected close date, or qualify out and clean up the pipeline.</p>
        <h3>Top 5 Must Win Opportunities</h3>
        <p>Top 5 Must Win Opportunities shows the opportunities that require priority focus to maximize your revenue in the immediate term. </p>
        <p>The Must Win opportunities that are listed are either suggested by Dealmaker or are opportunities that the Sales Manager or seller has manually indicated as Must Win opportunities.</p>
        <p>(Your system administrator has configured the ‘Must Win’ criteria for your company.)</p>
        <p>You would select a deal to be a Must Win in order to ensure that it is always ‘front-of-mind’ and receives the right level of attention to maximize your opportunity to win. </p>
        <p>Every deal that is Must Win should be the subject of a Test &amp; Improve session, so that you can uncover vulnerabilities, determine the optimum strategy to win, corral the necessary resources to be applied, and develop a set of actions to advance the opportunity.</p>
        <br />
		<h4>Selecting Must Win Opportunities</h4>
        <p>All deals are important, of course, but some opportunities are more strategic, and require more focus and potential resources to ensure the win. </p>
        <p>Maximizing sales performance results is all about prioritization. You want to make sure you are allocating your precious resources to opportunities that are strategically important. </p>
        <p>Strategically important may be defined in terms of absolute monetary value, a chance to develop a strategic position in an account, the introduction of a new product, defending a position with an existing customer against a competitor, or one of a myriad of other reasons.</p>
        <p>Think about it this way: Winning four deals out of seven is better than three deals out of ten.  If you can achieve this level of focus, the results are remarkable. Your absolute number of wins goes up by 33%, and your win rate goes from 30% (3/10) to 57% (4/7).  This is a much greater return on investment, and makes sure that you are not wasting resources on the other seven deals.</p>
        <p>Must Win opportunities (for this period) must be very well qualified, with a fully active selling engagement. And it must be reasonably well-advanced.  </p>
        <p>Must Win opportunities can have a projected date outside of the forecast period, but you are usually considering Must Win opportunities to be of a short-to-medium-term focus. </p>
        <p>Where opportunities have a longer horizon, and you are positioning for a deal in the future, they are likely to belong in Must Develop.</p>
        <p>Consider the following questions to guide your selection of Must Win deals:</p>
        <ol>
            <li>Is the opportunity of sufficient value that merits specific focused resources?</li>
            <li>Is it a strategic competitive replacement to establish a beachhead for future business?</li>
            <li>Is this a strategic or marquee account?</li>
            <li>Does it provide an opportunity to establish a reference account for a new product?</li>
            <li>Are you are defending a position against an important competitor?</li>
            <li>Does it provide an opportunity to establish a reference customer in a new industry?</li>
        </ol>
        <h3>Top 5 Must Develop Opportunities</h3>
        <p>Top 5 Must Develop Opportunities shows the opportunities that require attention, so that you can position for a future opportunity and maximize revenue in the medium-to-long term. </p>
        <p>The listed Must Develop opportunities are either suggested by Dealmaker or are opportunities that the Sales Manager or seller has manually selected.</p>
        <p>Great sales teams, the ones that consistently hit the number, understand that while it is important to be very clear on the sales opportunities that you need to win to make this quarter’s target, you have to continue to make progress on future opportunities. </p>
        <p>That’s why it's important to identify Must Develop opportunities. Just like Must Win opportunities, these are strategically important to win, but are not the deals you are planning to close in the immediate term.</p>
        <p>The key thing is that you proactively decide to adopt a Develop Strategy that allows you to continue to make progress without putting undue pressure on the natural rhythm of the customer’s buying cycle, or the other factors that cause you to determine that this one is better for next quarter. In any case you still need to take action.</p>
       
					</div>
