                <div class="point_text">
                    <h2>Top Risks to Forecast</h2>
					<p>This section deals with the major risks to your forecast:</p>
					
					<p> 1. Relying on Subjective Assessment</p>
					<p> 2. Using a Weighted Pipeline Model</p>
					<p> 3. Expecting Previously Forecasted Deals to ‘Close This Time’</p>
					<p> 4. Poor Data, or No Common Sales Language</p>
					<p> 5. Relying on a Small Number of Large Deals</p>
					
					                        
                    <div class="more_info">
					 <h3>1. Relying on Subjective Assessment</h3>
        <p>In many cases, the problem with your Forecast is that the included opportunities are often marked as Forecasted or Commit by the sales person using only their subjective assessment.  </p>
        <p>There are certainly situations where this is an accurate assessment, but statistically only 50% of deals that are forecasted actually close. So flipping a coin to determine whether a deal will close or not is, on average, as accurate as most forecasting practices.</p>
        <p>If you have applied a structured sales process, or utilize a structured sales methodology, it is more likely that you will identify weaker deals early. </p>
        <p>A simple check for Compelling Event, Solution Fit and Unique Business Value, Inside Support, and Access to Funds will help you select the winners.  </p>
        <p>Even without the application of a methodology, you can identify risks that are a function of deal activity, opportunity age, and velocity though the sales cycle.</p>
        <h3>2. Using a Weighted Pipeline Model</h3>
        <p>It can be more difficult to get an accurate determination of the closure likelihood of Possible deals, particularly when it is early in the forecast period.  </p>
        <p>A common practice that we would caution against is the ‘weighted pipeline’ model, where you take all of the Possible Opportunities and multiple their value by their closure probability, and then assume that this is a safe value to forecast. </p>
        <p> For example, if you have a $1,000,000 opportunity that 15% likely to close, and you have a $200,000 deal that is 75% likely to close, this approach will value both (in terms of their possible contribution to forecast) at $150,000.  </p>
        <p>Clearly this isn't terribly helpful.  In the first case, the customer never buys 15% or 75% of a solution, and secondly there are too many other factors in play to view the $1m deal and $200k deal as the same.</p>
        <h3>3. Expecting Previously Forecasted Deals to ‘Close This Time’</h3>
        <p>We have all been in this situation.  We didn't lose the deal last quarter – it just slipped into this quarter. </p>
        <p>This sometimes means that you have a qualification issue, but usually means that there is no Compelling Event identified by the customer.  </p>
        <p>When the age of an opportunity in your forecast is materially longer than your average winning sales cycle for that type of deal, the likelihood of your winning that deal is extremely low. </p>
        <p>A useful test for this type of opportunity is to simply ask the customer to explain the worst thing that would happen if they never embarked on this project. </p>
        <p> If the customer does not exhibit real concern and potentially serious impact, then the opportunity might not belong in the forecast.</p>
        <h3>4. Poor Data, or No Common Sales Language</h3>
        <p>If the data in Salesforce is inaccurate or incomplete, it is impossible for your sales forecast to be accurate.  </p>
        <p>There is then a lot of wasted resources applied to understanding the ‘real story’ behind each opportunity, and less time spent on activities that can help progress the deal. This is not in anyone’s interest. </p>
        <p>There is little value transacted when manager and seller have to spend time validating the forecast. </p>
        <p> Similarly, unless the whole organization has a common language that can be used to communicate clearly the current state of an opportunity, the likelihood of having a common assessment of whether a deal should be forecasted is reduced. </p>
        <p>Then you end up with unexpected losses and occasionally unexpected wins. In either case your forecast will be inaccurate.</p>
        <h3>5. Relying on a Small Number of Large Deals</h3>
        <p>If your forecast contains opportunities that are substantially larger that the size of deals that you normally win, they can obviously represent a significant swing factor in your results. </p>
        <p> If these large deals represent a disproportionate percentage of your forecasted number, and are not balanced by a reasonable number of average size deals, then your forecast is clearly at risk. </p>
        <p>If you find yourself in this situation during a forecast period. it is likely that you can do little to improve the balance of deals in time to change the outcome.  </p>
        <p>In that case you need to assess each of these large deals, mark them as Must Win if appropriate, and strategize each deal effectively to maximize your chance of winning.  </p>
        <p>At the same time you need to engage in business development activity to balance your future pipeline so that this is not a recurring situation.</p>
		
		
					</div>
                    <p><a href="javascript:void[0]" class="more_info_link">More...</a></p>
                </div>
            </li>
            <li class="clearfix">
                <div class="point_image"><img src="{!URLFOR($Resource.eLearning, 'images/icon5.png')}" /></div>
                <div class="point_text">
                    <h2>Best Practice</h2>
                    <ul>
            <li><p>Conduct Revenue Outlook calls weekly with each team member.</p><p>The purpose of these calls is to accurately project deals that can close inside the reporting period, and identify timely strategies for closing those deals.  This process enables the manager and seller to level-set on opportunities. It should be conducted according to a predictable routine.</p>
              </li>
            <li><p>Prepare in advance</p><p>Both manager and seller should get into a habit of coming to the call with the requisite information already in hand to have a productive meeting.  </p>
            <p>Review the opportunity status/details in Dealmaker (or other opportunity planning system) prior to the Revenue Outlook call and prepare questions.  In the manager’s case, the questions can be for clarification, but should be mainly focused on determining what assistance or guidance can be provided.</p>
          </li>
             </ul>
                    <div class="more_info">
					<ul>
					<li><p>Begin with Current State metrics, Forecast Value, Won, Projected and Possible.</p> <p>Identify gap to quota.  Discuss changes since the last call. Recognize achievement, and celebrate wins.</p>
           </li>
             <li><p>Validate Projected opportunities using verifiable outcomes for each sales stage to re-evaluate the likelihood of closing the opportunity, and refine strategies to help the process. </p><p>The goal is for seller and manager to maximize success, and to help the seller to succeed. If applicable, look for ways to close any quota gaps.</p>
            </li>
            <li><p>Evaluate High Risk deals, and schedule Test &amp; Improve (or 'Deal Review') sessions to mitigate risk and strengthen the strategy to win.</p></li>
            <li><p>For Must Win or High Risk deals, ensure that there is a detailed call or meeting plan for the next step in the process.  </p><p>Detailed call plans will ensure that you are well coordinated as a team, and that you have a clear understanding of key messages, competitive positioning, questions to ask, information to convey, and a common understanding of the minimal and optimal objectives for the call.</p>
            </li>
            <li><p>Review remaining Possible deals and Must Develop opportunities to identify situations where you may be able to accelerate sales cycles and maintain momentum for future forecast periods.</p></li>
            <li><p>Close out any opportunities that either should have been qualified out, or have no reasonable likelihood of winning.</p></li>
        </ul>
					</div>
